Scott: So, it's a good thing my work has this nice teleconferencing bridge we're going to use.

24
00:01:24,220 --> 00:01:25,131
Rym: Yep, so we'll get to see.

25
00:01:25,252 --> 00:01:29,719
Rym: And once again, we apologize for the audio quality of the interview bit.

26
00:01:30,081 --> 00:01:32,299
Rym: That's as good as the cell phones can do.

27
00:01:32,780 --> 00:01:40,400
Rym: But anyway, in the news, Wired is running a story about people who, using very little technology, track America's spy satellites.

28
00:01:41,040 --> 00:01:43,419
Rym: And apparently they've been doing this for the last ten, twenty years.

29
00:01:44,500 --> 00:01:44,904
Scott: Wait, wait.

30
00:01:45,005 --> 00:01:47,028
Scott: So, were they just looking at it with a telescope?

31
00:01:47,574 --> 00:01:52,460
Rym: Yeah, basically, the US, when they launch a spy satellite, do it kind of surreptitiously.

32
00:01:53,121 --> 00:01:58,709
Rym: They'll often announce a launch of something, but they'll launch it at a different time, or a different trajectory, or from a different site.

33
00:01:59,254 --> 00:02:04,720
Rym: And basically, the entire system of US spy satellites is secured only through obscurity.

34
00:02:05,800 --> 00:02:11,599
Rym: I mean, the satellites are painted certain colors and designed in certain ways to be hard to spot, but obscurity is really the only thing they've got going for them.

35
00:02:11,720 --> 00:02:16,099
Scott: You know, if you paint it completely black and non-reflective, you can't really see it.

36
00:02:16,683 --> 00:02:17,640
Rym: Because of, you know, space.

37
00:02:18,160 --> 00:02:23,240
Rym: One, they couldn't do that, because it needs to be reflective to reflect things like heat, and it needs solar panels and such.

38
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:25,900
Scott: You could face the solar panels away from the Earth.

39
00:02:26,661 --> 00:02:37,937
Rym: Two, more importantly than that, even a completely black object can be seen in space, because it stands out from, say, background radiation, or other brighter things that it blocks when it passes them.

40
00:02:39,520 --> 00:02:39,620
Rym: Yeah.

41
00:02:40,461 --> 00:02:47,700
Rym: So basically, these guys, and they work all over the world, and there's a lot of groups like Heavens Above and C-SAT-L are the two mentioned.

42
00:02:48,501 --> 00:03:01,311
Rym: They just kind of watch for them in the sky, and they all correlate their data, and once they get enough spottings of an individual satellite, or an individual object, they can usually do enough math to accurately predict the satellite's trajectory.

43
00:03:01,331 --> 00:03:04,545
Rym: And they've made big maps of all the spy satellites they've spotted out there.

44
00:03:05,576 --> 00:03:13,231
Rym: Now, the US doesn't like this so much, and they've been summoned and subpoenaed and told to shut down lots of times, but technically what they're doing is not at all illegal.

45
00:03:13,574 --> 00:03:14,140
Scott: No, it's not.

46
00:03:14,360 --> 00:03:20,959
Scott: And I don't know, if a judge said they were guilty of something, and there wasn't a new law saying you couldn't do that, I'd be pretty pissed off.

47
00:03:21,820 --> 00:03:27,799
Rym: Yeah, well, even the most asinine thing is that, say the government is angry about this, you know, hey, they're telling everyone where our spy satellites are.

48
00:03:27,860 --> 00:03:28,779
Scott: So now astronomy will be illegal?

49
00:03:30,284 --> 00:03:41,859
Rym: I submit that if a bunch of guys with some pieces of paper and binoculars and some telescopes can do this, I wouldn't put it past the foreign services of every other nation on this Earth to do the same thing.

50
00:03:42,920 --> 00:03:45,679
Scott: Yeah, the thing is, what do these spy satellites even do?

51
00:03:45,780 --> 00:03:48,528
Scott: All they can do, really, is take pictures and transmit data.

52
00:03:48,892 --> 00:03:50,345
Rym: Yeah, taking pictures is key.

53
00:03:50,446 --> 00:03:54,850
Rym: That's how the US does most of its ops when it comes to wartime, at least as far as I know.

54
00:03:54,871 --> 00:03:57,720
Scott: Well, yeah, taking pictures is key, but anyone can take freakin' pictures.

55
00:03:57,860 --> 00:04:01,139
Scott: You can take pictures of the spy plane, you can take pictures of anything, you know.

56
00:04:01,901 --> 00:04:06,891
Rym: No, spy planes are, you know, they can be shot down, they can be noticed, they're more expensive to use.

57
00:04:07,092 --> 00:04:07,920
Scott: Yeah, but here's the thing.

58
00:04:08,301 --> 00:04:16,386
Scott: I submit to you that a spy plane has more actual security than the spy satellite does if you take away the obscurity.

59
00:04:16,507 --> 00:04:21,980
Scott: Because a spy plane, alright, the only thing you can really do to a spy plane is maybe shoot it down, right?

60
00:04:22,344 --> 00:04:23,899
Rym: Like when we got our U-2 shot down.

61
00:04:24,320 --> 00:04:30,484
Scott: Right, but you know, they're really, really hard to shoot down, the spy planes, 'cause they go really, really fast and they're really, really high up.

62
00:04:31,272 --> 00:04:35,596
Scott: So, that's not, that'll happen sometimes, but not often enough to be.

63
00:04:35,940 --> 00:04:50,665
Rym: Well, the thing, from what I've read, the spy planes we have and all of our stealth bits are only effective against effectively third world nations, and Britain or France or any modern industrialized nation with a real military can just see all of our spy stuff.

64
00:04:51,069 --> 00:04:51,332
Rym: Oh, yeah.

65
00:04:51,372 --> 00:04:55,960
Rym: We've just never spied on anyone who had the capability to shoot us down or was willing to risk an international incident.

66
00:04:56,040 --> 00:04:56,948
Scott: Well, we do spy on them.

67
00:04:56,989 --> 00:04:59,639
Scott: We spy on them the old-fashioned way with James Bond and such.

68
00:05:00,460 --> 00:05:02,100
Rym: Yeah, we mostly just have satellites.

69
00:05:02,720 --> 00:05:02,862
Scott: Yeah.

70
00:05:03,595 --> 00:05:11,780
Scott: Still, the satellites, anyone can point a dish at them and, you know, collect the encrypted data and then see what it is eventually.

71
00:05:12,282 --> 00:05:13,260
Scott: It's not really so secure.

72
00:05:14,162 --> 00:05:15,737
Rym: That's not, they don't care at all about that.

73
00:05:15,777 --> 00:05:18,260
Rym: They care about people knowing when the satellites are passing over.

74
00:05:18,482 --> 00:05:23,208
Scott: Oh, so they don't actually care if someone knows the useless information of where the satellite is.

75
00:05:23,229 --> 00:05:24,905
Rym: Well, no, here's the thing.

76
00:05:24,925 --> 00:05:26,159
Rym: Say you know where the satellite is.

77
00:05:26,380 --> 00:05:35,391
Rym: Alright, then you know that spy satellites pass over your country X, Y, and Z, and there's a period of three hours every four days where no satellites can see you.

78
00:05:35,815 --> 00:05:38,319
Rym: That's when you have all the trucks with the uranium drive around.

79
00:05:39,500 --> 00:05:39,979
Scott: You know what?

80
00:05:40,060 --> 00:05:41,009
Rym: That's happened to the U.S.

81
00:05:41,049 --> 00:05:41,392
Rym: before.

82
00:05:41,413 --> 00:05:43,048
Scott: India did it, I think.

83
00:05:43,230 --> 00:05:44,825
Rym: Yeah, when they were developing their nuclear program.

84
00:05:44,845 --> 00:05:45,108
Rym: You know what?

85
00:05:45,128 --> 00:05:50,703
Scott: If India knows when the spy satellites are coming over, then the spy satellites are pretty much useless.

86
00:05:50,744 --> 00:05:53,759
Scott: We should stop wasting money on them and stop pestering these guys who see them.

87
00:05:54,860 --> 00:05:57,370
Scott: I think that's the best idea, because that means they're pretty much useless.

88
00:05:57,815 --> 00:06:08,420
Rym: Luckily, the article on Wired, it doesn't seem like they've been pestered a lot recently, so because I've known about this for a long time and it looks like the government's starting to realize that this isn't going to work so well.

89
00:06:08,580 --> 00:06:14,240
Rym: Either that or it's all a giant conspiracy and the real spy satellites are actually completely undetectable in magic.

90
00:06:14,604 --> 00:06:14,968
Scott: Could be.

91
00:06:15,149 --> 00:06:15,473
Scott: You know what?

92
00:06:15,493 --> 00:06:16,180
Scott: I got a better idea.

93
00:06:16,280 --> 00:06:18,400
Scott: Let's say they're not magic or undetectable.

94
00:06:18,980 --> 00:06:22,420
Scott: Just put up so many that there's always one passing over everywhere.

95
00:06:22,900 --> 00:06:25,616
Scott: That way, even if they know where they are, they can't really do anything about it.

96
00:06:25,636 --> 00:06:34,080
Rym: Well, China, not too long ago, asserted it's right that if it so desired, it could shoot down satellites.

97
00:06:34,600 --> 00:06:35,693
Scott: Oh, right, right, right.

98
00:06:35,754 --> 00:06:37,956
Rym: But then again, that was in retaliation to the U.S.

99
00:06:37,996 --> 00:06:39,128
Rym: saying the same thing first.

100
00:06:39,209 --> 00:06:42,159
Scott: Yeah, but seriously, shooting down a satellite is not easy.

101
00:06:43,164 --> 00:06:45,471
Scott: I mean, shooting down a satellite is harder than putting one up.

102
00:06:45,775 --> 00:06:46,765
Rym: Well, consider this, though.

103
00:06:46,866 --> 00:06:51,915
Rym: Putting one up, usually the thing you're putting up is extremely delicate and fragile and you have to be very careful with it.

104
00:06:51,936 --> 00:06:53,009
Scott: And you have to use a rocket.

105
00:06:53,536 --> 00:06:53,759
Rym: Yes.

106
00:06:54,582 --> 00:06:58,563
Rym: If you want to knock a satellite out of the sky, you don't need to shoot up a complex piece of equipment.

107
00:06:58,765 --> 00:07:03,028
Rym: You shoot up a rocket with a weight on it, and you just ram it into whatever you're shooting at.

108
00:07:03,048 --> 00:07:05,008
Scott: Yeah, but the rockets are expensive.

109
00:07:05,291 --> 00:07:07,594
Rym: The satellite costs four or five times more than the rocket.

110
00:07:08,018 --> 00:07:08,260
Scott: Really?

111
00:07:08,420 --> 00:07:08,906
Rym: If not more.

112
00:07:09,149 --> 00:07:10,708
Scott: Well, some satellites cost more.

113
00:07:10,748 --> 00:07:11,599
Scott: Some satellites are cheap.

114
00:07:12,400 --> 00:07:13,473
Scott: You know, it depends on the satellite.

115
00:07:13,493 --> 00:07:15,191
Scott: Like, a TV satellite is kind of expensive.

116
00:07:15,211 --> 00:07:15,918
Rym: Keep in mind that...

117
00:07:16,120 --> 00:07:18,948
Scott: But just like a camera and a solar cell isn't so expensive.

118
00:07:18,988 --> 00:07:22,826
Rym: Keep in mind that even a tiny tiny glancing blow will just destroy a satellite.

119
00:07:22,908 --> 00:07:23,799
Scott: Oh, of course, of course.

120
00:07:24,441 --> 00:07:27,573
Scott: But the point is that the rocket expense is equal either way.

121
00:07:27,877 --> 00:07:34,525
Scott: So if I was going to destroy a satellite, I would always, you know, have my rocket expenses and put one up whenever I destroyed one.

122
00:07:34,545 --> 00:07:37,028
Rym: Ah, yeah, because you're a rocket scientist.

123
00:07:37,695 --> 00:07:38,159
Scott: I could be.

124
00:07:39,950 --> 00:07:45,248
Rym: Lucky, I just thought this was cool, and props to these guys for doing this awesome hobby.

125
00:07:45,289 --> 00:07:47,018
Rym: It's kind of like trainspotting, only not as dumb.

126
00:07:48,422 --> 00:07:48,685
Scott: Alright.

127
00:07:49,310 --> 00:07:51,814
Scott: Well, there's this girl named Inga something.

128
00:07:52,238 --> 00:07:52,986
Scott: I don't know her last name.

129
00:07:53,531 --> 00:07:58,049
Scott: And she, I think she was an intern, or... Nope.

130
00:07:58,380 --> 00:08:04,784
Scott: She actually had a job as a legal clerk at a medium-sized intellectual property law firm in Midtown New York.

131
00:08:05,107 --> 00:08:05,491
Rym: Alright.

132
00:08:06,198 --> 00:08:09,512
Scott: And she wrote an article for The Village Voice called Code Warriors.

133
00:08:10,279 --> 00:08:17,168
Scott: And it talked all about the free culture movement, specifically the NYU group that, you know, involved in that sort of thing.

134
00:08:18,258 --> 00:08:19,899
Scott: And you know how DRM sucks.

135
00:08:20,722 --> 00:08:21,895
Rym: Alright, something we can all agree on.

136
00:08:22,138 --> 00:08:22,260
Rym: Yep.

137
00:08:22,662 --> 00:08:29,918
Scott: And she was fired from her job at the IP law firm for holding views contradictory to what the firm does.

138
00:08:31,846 --> 00:08:40,741
Scott: And it was weird because apparently the firm, like, overemphasized her right to express those views, but then it still fired her.

139
00:08:41,489 --> 00:08:42,155
Rym: Uh-huh.

140
00:08:42,376 --> 00:08:44,033
Scott: It's like, "Oh, you can keep saying this.

141
00:08:44,073 --> 00:08:44,761
Scott: We have no problem with

142
00:08:44,781 --> 00:08:44,902
Scott: that.".

143
00:08:44,922 --> 00:08:45,468
Scott: But you're fired.

144
00:08:45,892 --> 00:08:50,640
Rym: See, it's technically, it's a gray area there, but it, well, one, they're lawyers.

145
00:08:50,820 --> 00:08:53,529
Rym: They probably know what they're doing, but it looks like it's technically legal.

146
00:08:54,135 --> 00:09:02,699
Rym: Because in the United States at least, and in states that are right-to-work states, which New York is, you can hire and fire some people for any reason at any time with no warning.

147
00:09:02,881 --> 00:09:03,588
Rym: Perfectly legally.

148
00:09:04,114 --> 00:09:06,919
Rym: The only things you can't discriminate against are protected classes.

149
00:09:07,480 --> 00:09:11,189
Rym: Things like race, religion, gender.

150
00:09:11,209 --> 00:09:11,900
Scott: Sexuality.

151
00:09:12,940 --> 00:09:13,486
Rym: Yeah.

152
00:09:13,971 --> 00:09:15,692
Rym: Actually, that one's still hotly debated.

153
00:09:15,712 --> 00:09:16,320
Rym: Yeah, that sucks.

154
00:09:17,161 --> 00:09:18,030
Rym: Because it should be protected.

155
00:09:18,050 --> 00:09:18,879
Scott: It should be on the list.

156
00:09:19,060 --> 00:09:20,920
Rym: And a lot of other things should be on the list, too, but they aren't.

157
00:09:21,220 --> 00:09:21,402
Scott: Yeah.

158
00:09:21,848 --> 00:09:22,314
Rym: But anyway.

159
00:09:22,334 --> 00:09:23,448
Scott: You know what shouldn't be on the list?

160
00:09:23,833 --> 00:09:24,056
Rym: Huh?

161
00:09:24,218 --> 00:09:24,380
Rym: Wait.

162
00:09:25,340 --> 00:09:33,019
Scott: Alright, so, um, the point is, is that however, uh, legal this is, it still smells real bad.

163
00:09:33,500 --> 00:09:37,240
Rym: Yeah, I would definitely call, it's one of those situations that I would describe as legal, but unethical.

164
00:09:37,840 --> 00:09:37,929
Scott: Yeah.

165
00:09:38,780 --> 00:09:40,680
Scott: There are a lot of things that are legal that are just no good.

166
00:09:40,961 --> 00:09:44,352
Rym: Yeah, like all the bribery in Congress, uh...

167
00:09:44,373 --> 00:09:49,000
Scott: It's like, and the thing is, is she really wants to be an IP lawyer, and she still plans to be one.

168
00:09:49,080 --> 00:09:51,384
Scott: That's like what she wants to be with her life.

169
00:09:51,667 --> 00:09:57,646
Scott: And that's, she was working there seriously, but she just happens to have a different view on IP lawyer-ness.

170
00:09:58,009 --> 00:10:04,420
Rym: So it's kinda like, Now, was it for her views on IP itself, or just for her views on DRM specifically?

171
00:10:04,660 --> 00:10:10,459
Scott: It was because of this article she wrote that was published in the Village Voice that was anti-DRMs.

172
00:10:10,880 --> 00:10:18,112
Rym: Alright, now, I submit that an IP law firm would have a vested interest in wanting DRM to go away.

173
00:10:18,495 --> 00:10:26,279
Rym: Because without DRM, the laws are still in place, but now it's a lot easier to infringe, and thus they'll have a lot more business helping companies sue people.

174
00:10:26,865 --> 00:10:27,168
Scott: Mmm.

175
00:10:27,955 --> 00:10:38,237
Scott: The other thing is, um, I think the line that got them was, "Oh, if there's a law, if there are laws I believe are wrong, I will break

176
00:10:38,297 --> 00:10:38,398
Scott: them.".

177
00:10:38,904 --> 00:10:40,420
Scott: And that's what the girl said in the article.

178
00:10:40,500 --> 00:10:42,034
Scott: So I'm like, "Oh, I say the same

179
00:10:42,054 --> 00:10:42,216
Scott: thing.".

180
00:10:42,781 --> 00:10:44,240
Scott: But apparently lawyers don't like that.

181
00:10:45,042 --> 00:10:46,279
Rym: Uh, I guess I can understand that.

182
00:10:47,910 --> 00:10:51,193
Scott: Uh, we can't have any, you know, civilly disobedient lawyers.

183
00:10:52,683 --> 00:10:55,672
Rym: There's always that funny poster that's on FARC whenever something like this comes up.

184
00:10:56,056 --> 00:11:00,319
Rym: It's a picture that says civil disobedience is still disobedience and it's just a cop beating the hell out of someone.

185
00:11:01,420 --> 00:11:18,039
Rym: [laughter] So, my thing of the day, it's not particularly a new thing, but it amused me to great lengths while I was on that conference call I spoke about earlier at work today.

186
00:11:18,883 --> 00:11:22,665
Rym: It's an archive of the endings of a whole bunch of video games.

187
00:11:23,230 --> 00:11:25,433
Scott: Did they have the ending to Silver Surfer for the NES?

188
00:11:25,837 --> 00:11:26,928
Rym: Uh, I don't believe I saw it.

189
00:11:27,211 --> 00:11:27,494
Scott: Damn.

190
00:11:27,817 --> 00:11:34,868
Rym: But I watched the ending to Shadowrun because as much as I love that game, I don't have, you know, a year of my life to beat it again.

191
00:11:34,888 --> 00:11:34,969
Rym: Yeah.

192
00:11:36,822 --> 00:11:41,093
Scott: All those games that just are not worth it, the endings online are pretty good.

193
00:11:41,154 --> 00:11:42,990
Rym: [laughter] And it works really great.

194
00:11:43,011 --> 00:11:45,220
Rym: Just a flash site and it just plays the ending in a loop.

195
00:11:46,060 --> 00:11:46,726
Scott: Eh, not bad.

196
00:11:47,089 --> 00:11:48,299
Rym: I don't know what else I can say about it.

197
00:11:48,881 --> 00:11:51,007
Scott: Any, uh, particularly interesting games in there?

198
00:11:51,028 --> 00:11:52,463
Rym: Uh, actually no.

199
00:11:52,523 --> 00:11:53,898
Rym: It's pretty much really generic.

200
00:11:53,918 --> 00:11:55,580
Rym: There's nothing off the wall or anything.

201
00:11:56,387 --> 00:12:00,710
Scott: Uh, see that would have made it really priceless if it was like game endings you've never seen.

202
00:12:00,831 --> 00:12:02,226
Rym: No, they were all game endings.

203
00:12:02,367 --> 00:12:04,207
Rym: either I've seen or I don't care about.

204
00:12:04,773 --> 00:12:05,300
Scott: Uh, that sucks.

205
00:12:06,782 --> 00:12:12,690
