351
00:20:57,661 --> 00:21:02,740
Rym: But basically, we've already introduced the topic at hand, the Otakon Artist Alley issue.

352
00:21:03,361 --> 00:21:12,499
Rym: And considering that we saw you in the community about it and we know you to be generally articulate and interesting, we figured you would be a good person to ask about this.

353
00:21:13,060 --> 00:21:13,144
Rym: Okay.

354
00:21:13,500 --> 00:21:17,120
Rym: So tell us a bit about this Save Artist Alley live journal community.

355
00:21:17,881 --> 00:21:23,480
Guest: Well, before I begin, I just want to state that most of this is just coming from my personal opinion, you know, standard disclaimer stuff.

356
00:21:23,741 --> 00:21:24,799
Guest: I am not an Otakon staffer.

357
00:21:25,440 --> 00:21:33,160
Guest: I have never been part of the running of Otakon, blah, blah, blah, not a law student nor an artist, just, you know, concerned Joe citizen here.

358
00:21:33,621 --> 00:21:55,100
Guest: But from my understanding, the community that we formed, Save Artist Alley, is a community dedicated to getting people involved with returning Artist Alley to what we've known it to be, a place where people can gather and show what they've created, any creative works that might represent any sort of anime, manga, video game, any sort of topic or property they care to present.

359
00:21:55,920 --> 00:22:11,600
Guest: And we're centered around the idea that – and this is just roughly me quoting since I'm not really in charge of the community or anything – we're centered around the idea that the spirit of the law is conflicting with the letter of the law and Otakon is taking overzealous steps in order to preserve the letter.

360
00:22:12,340 --> 00:22:31,120
Guest: Now, we feel, mostly, and I'm not sure if there's any real single line that everybody's trying on here, but I think that what we're really going for is the idea that fan art, as an institution, as a creative work, is a protected form of expression.

361
00:22:32,100 --> 00:22:33,640
Guest: I mean, I could draw a parallel for you.

362
00:22:33,640 --> 00:22:44,919
Guest: Now, what this would go on with would be, let's say, I'm an artist and as part of my education, I paint a copy of Van Gogh's Starry Night, you know, the famous painting, right?

363
00:22:45,600 --> 00:22:50,318
Guest: Now, let's say I paint this and it's a good replica and somebody's interested in buying it.

364
00:22:50,821 --> 00:22:56,328
Guest: And it is clearly marked Starry Night, as interpreted by Mike Pfeffer, you know, 10 bucks.

365
00:22:56,750 --> 00:22:59,201
Guest: So they give me the $10.

366
00:22:59,201 --> 00:23:00,126
Guest: I give them the painting.

367
00:23:00,568 --> 00:23:02,659
Guest: I've just made money off of Vincent Van.

368
00:23:02,679 --> 00:23:02,860
Guest: Gogh.

369
00:23:03,503 --> 00:23:05,271
Guest: Now, is Vincent Van Gogh going to sue me?

370
00:23:05,613 --> 00:23:06,456
Guest: Can he sue me?

371
00:23:06,617 --> 00:23:07,220
Guest: Or his estate?

372
00:23:07,340 --> 00:23:12,905
Guest: Can his legal representatives collect damages or criminal penalties from me for doing this?

373
00:23:13,609 --> 00:23:25,920
Guest: I say that with American copyright law, and to a lesser extent, international treaty, does not cover this effectively to the point where Oticon needs to take such draconian measures in order to enforce their policy.

374
00:23:26,900 --> 00:23:40,840
Rym: - Well, I can say that I've got a large compilation of various quotes from staffers on this, because Jim Valls, the head of Oticon, pretty much put a moratorium on the staff commenting on this issue in light of the, well, flame wars that have appeared on their forums.

375
00:23:41,780 --> 00:23:47,320
Guest: But it appears-- - You know, when you think about it, Jim Valls is really just trying to do some effective damage control.

376
00:23:47,461 --> 00:23:48,254
Guest: I don't think he's involved.

377
00:23:48,275 --> 00:23:48,478
Rym: - Oh, yes.

378
00:23:49,641 --> 00:23:57,439
Rym: I definitely don't blame him for what he did, because honestly, their forums exploded and Anime News Network reported on it, and then he corrected them when they apparently made a mistake.

379
00:23:58,023 --> 00:24:08,380
Rym: But apparently, as far as I can tell, and this is based on my analysis of things the staff has said, they have not stated to me directly what has happened, but there's no legal pressure.

380
00:24:08,640 --> 00:24:15,840
Rym: There's been no--like, a lot of people have speculated that maybe one of the anime companies cracked down on them, or maybe the dealers are complaining about competition.

381
00:24:17,101 --> 00:24:29,319
Rym: But Rachel Ann, who's the head of Artist Alley, said, and I quote here when she was asked why this suddenly became an issue after 10 years of it being a non-issue, quote, "I'll take the blame credit for that.

382
00:24:29,681 --> 00:24:35,836
Rym: "It was my decision to act on this for Otakon 2006, "and I thank our presidente and the Otakon staff for supporting

383
00:24:35,856 --> 00:24:35,937
Rym: me.".

384
00:24:36,960 --> 00:24:43,259
Guest: - Okay, I remember seeing that quote, and I also remember some of the surroundings, some of the actual other things she said concerning that.

385
00:24:43,740 --> 00:24:46,340
Guest: You know, just to paraphrase Rachel Ann, I have nothing against her.

386
00:24:46,801 --> 00:24:47,610
Guest: I don't know who she is.

387
00:24:47,630 --> 00:24:48,520
Guest: I've never met her before.

388
00:24:49,220 --> 00:24:54,200
Guest: Apparently, she encountered some sort of violation of an intellectual property that she herself had created.

389
00:24:54,703 --> 00:24:57,620
Rym: I think it was some sort of play or puppet show.

390
00:24:57,800 --> 00:25:22,600
Guest: Now, I understand that if she's coming from a perspective of a chairperson in charge of a department, let's say, just to back into more organizational terms, if she, acting as a chair of the department, had some sort of input in order to formulate a better policy, and this is just, you know, how to craft something together, I think that what might have happened here was that she used this policy as a little bit of an overzealous personal example.

391
00:25:23,303 --> 00:25:26,980
Guest: Now, this is not something that you need to rule out entirely, don't get me wrong.

392
00:25:27,500 --> 00:25:35,260
Guest: Personal experience can help a great deal in making policy, in making rules and regulations, even for an organization like Otakon.

393
00:25:36,021 --> 00:25:53,038
Guest: However, I think that what might have happened, and I really would have loved to see the minutes, the logs of that meeting where this policy was formulated, I think what happened was just a battle of here is what could happen, here's where I'm coming from as a creator, here's how I feel, and here's what we need to do to take steps against that.

394
00:25:54,100 --> 00:25:59,120
Rym: And for what I see, that seems like it's a very good idea as to what happened.

395
00:25:59,720 --> 00:26:11,840
Rym: I mean, looking at the conversations that took place before Jim Voll has kind of stepped in and started speaking for Otakon, Rachel Ann very specifically clarified the policy and did clarify it to be a very draconian thing.

396
00:26:12,540 --> 00:26:17,080
Rym: She said that chibi art or chibi art would not be okay because it's not considered parody.

397
00:26:17,140 --> 00:26:25,580
Rym: She said specifically that yaoi of characters is not parody, but rather exploitation of a licensed copyright character and will not be allowed.

398
00:26:26,721 --> 00:26:26,983
Guest: I see.

399
00:26:27,425 --> 00:26:33,919
Guest: That's where – I just want to state that I'm not a yaoi fan, and believe me, my little talk today is going to be full of disclaimers.

400
00:26:34,720 --> 00:26:35,262
Scott: Neither are we.

401
00:26:36,928 --> 00:26:40,259
Scott: We're fans of making fun of yaoi, not actually enjoying it.

402
00:26:40,901 --> 00:26:41,383
Guest: Exactly.

403
00:26:41,744 --> 00:26:44,251
Guest: But to each their own, I say.

404
00:26:44,692 --> 00:26:50,580
Guest: And if it's going to be a form of exploitation, then they're going to have to define the exploitation that's happening here.

405
00:26:51,040 --> 00:26:56,896
Guest: If somebody wants to draw as horrible as I feel using this example, Ed, Al, yaoi, come on.

406
00:26:58,400 --> 00:26:59,466
Guest: That's not going to be great.

407
00:26:59,848 --> 00:27:01,719
Guest: It's not really my cup of tea.

408
00:27:02,480 --> 00:27:03,571
Rym: Oh, I've seen worse.

409
00:27:03,652 --> 00:27:04,440
Rym: Have you read Death Note?

410
00:27:05,401 --> 00:27:06,747
Guest: Oh, I've heard of it.

411
00:27:07,209 --> 00:27:09,460
Guest: And believe me, I go on image boards, man.

412
00:27:09,520 --> 00:27:11,909
Guest: I know about half of the yaoi that goes on the entire internet.

413
00:27:11,950 --> 00:27:12,331
Guest: It's horrible.

414
00:27:16,542 --> 00:27:17,245
Guest: And it's out there.

415
00:27:17,586 --> 00:27:20,580
Guest: And it is used, and it does fall back under the same thing.

416
00:27:20,760 --> 00:27:33,454
Guest: Even if you're drawing just Ed, Al hanging out, getting his automail fixed, if something's going on that is part of an intellectual property, even if it's not yaoi, it's still under Rachel Ann's definition of the phrase

417
00:27:33,555 --> 00:27:34,258
Guest: "exploitation.".

418
00:27:34,801 --> 00:27:41,119
Guest: If you want to go through a dictionary definition of exploitation, it's going to fall under a very different flock of geese here.

419
00:27:41,820 --> 00:27:43,325
Guest: We're not exploiting.

420
00:27:44,167 --> 00:27:48,360
Guest: This is basically expression that's really coming into question.

421
00:27:48,540 --> 00:27:52,360
Guest: How does an artist express themselves with an established object?

422
00:27:52,520 --> 00:27:54,760
Guest: How does an artist bring this about?

423
00:27:55,440 --> 00:27:59,900
Guest: And there's a lot of legal definitions that I'm not sure have fully been addressed here.

424
00:28:00,381 --> 00:28:02,919
Guest: I'd like to hear what the Oticon legal staff has to say about this.

425
00:28:04,704 --> 00:28:05,165
Scott: Yes.

426
00:28:06,629 --> 00:28:18,470
Scott: When at first I thought this might have been something the Oticon lawyers had come up with and told them to implement, but then when you noticed they didn't do anything about the cosplay or the AMVs, I said, "Oh, maybe they

427
00:28:18,490 --> 00:28:18,711
Scott: didn't.".

428
00:28:19,073 --> 00:28:22,738
Scott: And it turns out that as of now, they haven't actually talked to the lawyers yet.

429
00:28:23,580 --> 00:28:30,200
Rym: Well, apparently the lawyer was sick, and they had a horrible flu for the past week, and that's the only reason he hasn't reviewed this policy.

430
00:28:31,261 --> 00:28:42,979
Rym: But regarding the anime music videos and the cosplay, I do know that Oticon pays ASCAP license fees or something along those lines in order to be able to use the music for the AMVs, and they get the blessing of the industry to show them.

431
00:28:43,800 --> 00:28:50,824
Rym: And as for the cosplay, their insurance policy, as far as my understanding goes, once again, I'm not Oticon's staff either.

432
00:28:50,845 --> 00:29:00,615
Rym: Their insurance policy covers public performances of arts, and selling an art is not considered a public performance.

433
00:29:00,715 --> 00:29:03,688
Rym: It's considered a paid performance or a paid what you call it.

434
00:29:04,069 --> 00:29:06,399
Rym: So it's not legal covering for the other two.

435
00:29:07,060 --> 00:29:23,298
Rym: But when it comes to artist Allie, I actually pointed out to them, and Rachel Ann actually thought about it, and she's considering asking the lawyer about it, that by actively pursuing a policy of cracking down on copyright law, Oticon is actually opening itself up to liability as opposed to closing it.

436
00:29:25,101 --> 00:29:28,980
Scott: There's also the issue that in artist Allie, they're selling things to profit.

437
00:29:29,500 --> 00:29:36,372
Scott: You've got fan art, and you're trying to make money off of it, whereas the AMVs and the cosplays is just entertainment value.

438
00:29:36,472 --> 00:29:38,260
Scott: You're not actually selling anything to make money.

439
00:29:39,520 --> 00:29:40,243
Guest: Well, that's true.

440
00:29:40,263 --> 00:29:47,860
Guest: And I do think that it is necessary for copyright holders to act on that infringement, but however, that's in the hands of the copyright holder to engage in.

441
00:29:48,442 --> 00:29:50,910
Guest: For example, I heard that this is completely anecdotal.

442
00:29:50,930 --> 00:29:53,880
Guest: I could be way off base or even completely wrong.

443
00:29:54,500 --> 00:30:04,500
Guest: At Katsu 05, and I know at Oticon 04, there was a table in the artist Allie that was selling hats, hand-made little hats, and among those hats were interpretations of characters from FMA.

444
00:30:05,141 --> 00:30:07,651
Guest: He had a little Ed and Al hat.

445
00:30:07,671 --> 00:30:09,600
Guest: It was cute if you like that sort of thing.

446
00:30:10,100 --> 00:30:27,346
Guest: Funimation found out about this, and they had the person who was making them cease and desist, but in another wonderful twist of fate that could just be internet lies or complete utter truth, I think that Vic Mignogna himself will put in the rover for a couple of hats, just a personal commission

447
00:30:27,386 --> 00:30:27,909
Rym: from the

448
00:30:29,274 --> 00:30:29,656
Guest: artist.

449
00:30:29,676 --> 00:30:40,190
Guest: This could be completely wrong, but in this case, I don't see this, the artist Allie, and I could be legally incorrect, I don't see artist Allie as a public performance.

450
00:30:40,350 --> 00:30:43,240
Guest: I don't see it as an art presentation.

451
00:30:43,461 --> 00:30:45,590
Guest: I don't see it as a viewing of artworks.

452
00:30:46,052 --> 00:30:58,119
Guest: I see more of a commercial enterprise, but in this commercial enterprise, when you're dealing with something that is not necessarily the exact item that is under copyright protection, that is where the big question comes up.

453
00:30:58,581 --> 00:31:08,479
Guest: Is fan art an actual commercial profit off of an intellectual property, or is it simply an interpretation of an intellectual property as viewed through the eyes of artist X?

454
00:31:09,062 --> 00:31:22,900
Guest: And when you take away that interpretation, when you take away that ability to create, and then to distribute that creativity, and yes, we're talking about for money here, but we are talking about for works by artist X, not by Funimation, not by ATB Films.

455
00:31:23,461 --> 00:31:26,600
Guest: Yes, they own the copyright, but are they selling copies of the DVD?

456
00:31:27,201 --> 00:31:29,740
Guest: Are they selling cells that were made in the animation?

457
00:31:30,321 --> 00:31:32,440
Guest: Are they selling official merchandise that's been bootlegged?

458
00:31:33,281 --> 00:31:41,860
Guest: What I think this new policy is doing is equating the bootlegged anime that we see in the dealer's room to fan art, to individually created works of art.

459
00:31:42,560 --> 00:31:49,559
Guest: I mean, even if we're just talking – I mean, just last year I got a pin of Haro from Gundam C, which I think is totally awesome.

460
00:31:52,203 --> 00:31:53,529
Rym: I bought a little one.

461
00:31:53,871 --> 00:31:55,699
Rym: Washcloth for my girlfriend, and she loved it.

462
00:31:56,741 --> 00:31:58,025
Guest: Those are just totally great.

463
00:31:58,386 --> 00:32:02,040
Guest: And here's just an individual piece of creative art.

464
00:32:02,241 --> 00:32:02,924
Guest: This is a button.

465
00:32:02,944 --> 00:32:03,729
Guest: Look at the pins.

466
00:32:03,849 --> 00:32:05,820
Guest: Somebody with a pin press adds anime bits.

467
00:32:06,280 --> 00:32:07,243
Guest: It's got Haro on it.

468
00:32:07,404 --> 00:32:07,665
Guest: Yes.

469
00:32:08,167 --> 00:32:09,150
Guest: Is Bandai making this?

470
00:32:09,551 --> 00:32:09,792
Guest: No.

471
00:32:10,153 --> 00:32:11,398
Guest: Is it being marketed anywhere?

472
00:32:11,418 --> 00:32:11,458
Guest: No.

473
00:32:12,440 --> 00:32:18,566
Guest: Is this a Bandai product that is produced under license of Bandai under their sole control to distribute as they see fit?

474
00:32:19,088 --> 00:32:19,289
Guest: No.

475
00:32:19,751 --> 00:32:21,980
Guest: Is this something that one person sat down and made?

476
00:32:22,400 --> 00:32:26,297
Guest: Is this something that one person has interpreted from their intellectual property?

477
00:32:26,759 --> 00:32:26,940
Guest: Yes.

478
00:32:27,502 --> 00:32:34,446
Guest: Is it harming Bandai by producing this, which they do not have any production of or verifiable interest in?

479
00:32:34,948 --> 00:32:36,674
Guest: As far as we can tell, no.

480
00:32:36,754 --> 00:32:38,400
Guest: It does not harm the individual company.

481
00:32:39,261 --> 00:32:40,564
Rym: On that point, I agree with you.

482
00:32:41,146 --> 00:32:47,684
Rym: And I guess that kind of shows the point that this is a very legal gray area, as you elaborated.

483
00:32:48,266 --> 00:32:52,900
Rym: And I feel that it's not Otakon's place to try to enforce it.

484
00:32:53,321 --> 00:32:55,427
Rym: But Otakon should obviously comply.

485
00:32:56,169 --> 00:33:03,600
Rym: If a dealer or a producer actually wants to stop someone and they have the legal right to do so, then they can deal with it on their own.

486
00:33:03,700 --> 00:33:04,524
Rym: Otakon should help them.

487
00:33:04,986 --> 00:33:07,660
Rym: But I don't think Otakon should be enforcing a policy on their own.

488
00:33:08,520 --> 00:33:08,922
Guest: Exactly.

489
00:33:09,163 --> 00:33:11,070
Guest: Look at the Digital Millennium Copyright Act.

490
00:33:11,111 --> 00:33:13,380
Guest: This is big news for a lot of tech people.

491
00:33:14,200 --> 00:33:14,883
Guest: And it takes.

492
00:33:14,944 --> 00:33:22,276
Guest: every now and then, there's some big bust that involves an ISP having to turn over server logs to somebody that's using Kazaa or something else like that.

493
00:33:22,296 --> 00:33:24,847
Guest: You know, "Oh my God, they're still using the old version of Napster

494
00:33:24,907 --> 00:33:25,409
Guest: Nodes.".

495
00:33:26,012 --> 00:33:32,936
Guest: Well, what happens with the DMCA is that the government or the complainant in the party has to deliver a subpoena.

496
00:33:32,956 --> 00:33:37,671
Guest: They have to get on the record and put in the complaint to the ISP, who then provides the logs.

497
00:33:38,032 --> 00:33:43,633
Guest: The ISPs are not responsible for patrolling these networks, although most of them do, just on their own.

498
00:33:43,653 --> 00:33:46,584
Guest: They are not responsible for handing things over.

499
00:33:47,327 --> 00:33:52,703
Rym: And in fact, that is the liability I was speaking about when I talked about Otakon opening themselves up.

500
00:33:53,967 --> 00:34:00,165
Rym: ISPs have common carrier status, meaning that they are not actually responsible for what goes over their wires.

501
00:34:00,626 --> 00:34:15,360
Rym: However, if they choose at any time to actually invoke control over what goes over the wires, they have now legally opened themselves up to the fact that they can be held responsible for failing to act in a specific situation, because they've shown that they can act.

502
00:34:16,040 --> 00:34:25,014
Rym: And by Otakon actively enforcing this, they're saying that they can act, and thus they can be held legally helpable if they do not act, which I could see them not acting.

503
00:34:25,054 --> 00:34:27,719
Rym: if there's eight staffers trying to police three to a hundred artists.

504
00:34:29,440 --> 00:34:38,795
Guest: Well, I think that even with just those eight staffers, they can at least do something if they are forced to do so, if they're subpoenaed, if they are legally given a cease and desist.

505
00:34:38,835 --> 00:34:43,011
Guest: That's why a company cannot just march in and say, "Hey, you're being sued for distributing this,".

506
00:34:43,493 --> 00:34:45,380
Guest: and they're not properly wanting the artist.

507
00:34:46,080 --> 00:34:52,882
Guest: I mean, let's say ADV doesn't like the fact that I'm selling Excel Saga, what sort of Excel Saga merchandise can I think of?

508
00:34:52,982 --> 00:34:54,507
Guest: Excel Saga lunchboxes.

509
00:34:55,330 --> 00:35:04,980
Guest: They don't have Excel Saga lunchboxes, fresh Menchie involved, but I don't think they have any on their sale roster.

510
00:35:05,600 --> 00:35:07,068
Guest: And if they don't, what if I want to make them?

511
00:35:07,128 --> 00:35:09,460
Guest: And they just march in and say, "No, you can't do this.

512
00:35:09,520 --> 00:35:10,163
Guest: You're being

513
00:35:10,183 --> 00:35:10,706
Guest: sued.".

514
00:35:10,726 --> 00:35:12,113
Guest: Here I am saying, "Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

515
00:35:12,233 --> 00:35:13,600
Guest: I didn't know you had an interest in this.

516
00:35:13,720 --> 00:35:14,524
Guest: I know you own Excel

517
00:35:14,564 --> 00:35:14,986
Guest: Saga.".

518
00:35:15,027 --> 00:35:17,720
Guest: Yeah, but you don't own any Excel Saga lunchboxes.

519
00:35:18,700 --> 00:35:22,937
Guest: Without any proper oversight, then, ADV can just handle it down no matter what.

520
00:35:23,118 --> 00:35:23,500
Guest: I like ADV.

521
00:35:23,740 --> 00:35:31,920
Guest: Dave Williams is a good guy coming out to cons and doing all this good stuff, despite what I have against the voice actors at some points, but that's another podcast entirely.

522
00:35:33,643 --> 00:35:33,743
Rym: Yes.

523
00:35:33,763 --> 00:35:34,767
Rym: So here's a question for you.

524
00:35:35,048 --> 00:35:38,500
Rym: Suppose the policy goes into play as it is written now.

525
00:35:38,980 --> 00:35:41,520
Rym: What do you think will be the effect on Artist Alley this year?

526
00:35:42,620 --> 00:35:44,791
Guest: Well, for one thing, the spirit is going to be different.

527
00:35:44,851 --> 00:35:49,768
Guest: I can't really say about the actual numbers, but it's going to be fundamentally altered.

528
00:35:50,350 --> 00:36:00,280
Guest: I say, for one thing, that we're talking with First Amendment territory here, wherein the right to express is being basically taken down, and how many Otaku have the funds to fight this?

529
00:36:00,721 --> 00:36:02,831
Guest: How many people have the time and effort to do so, even more?

530
00:36:02,851 --> 00:36:20,270
Guest: If you just walk into Artist Alley, and you have – I always perennially think of just the kid who's 14, 15 years old, no real resources, finally managed to come to his first Otakon, and he or she wants to pick up his or her favorite drawing of character.

531
00:36:20,290 --> 00:36:21,295
Guest: They like Winry.

532
00:36:21,315 --> 00:36:22,580
Guest: They want their Winry drawing.

533
00:36:23,200 --> 00:36:24,223
Guest: And it's not there.

534
00:36:24,564 --> 00:36:25,427
Guest: You can't buy this.

535
00:36:25,648 --> 00:36:41,640
Guest: You cannot go into this one area where individual artists who get no real exposure in any other mass form, unless you go around deviantART for fun, they don't really have the chance to market their wares, to show their skills in a way that's applicable to Otaku.

536
00:36:42,242 --> 00:36:46,660
Guest: I mean, there are some incredibly talented artists down in the alley.

537
00:36:46,820 --> 00:36:48,932
Guest: I mean, there's this one guy who I idolize.

538
00:36:48,952 --> 00:36:50,400
Guest: He does fantastic megadrawings.

539
00:36:50,940 --> 00:36:54,520
Guest: I bought a fine printer from him of an arm sleeve from Full Metal Panic.

540
00:36:55,121 --> 00:36:57,953
Guest: I fully intend to get one when he starts doing some Gundam scene work.

541
00:36:58,737 --> 00:36:59,480
Guest: What if he's not there?

542
00:36:59,580 --> 00:37:03,095
Guest: What if he's just drawing generic Megabot 2000s?

543
00:37:03,356 --> 00:37:07,053
Guest: That's all well and good, but I don't want generic Megabot 2000s.

544
00:37:07,093 --> 00:37:08,479
Guest: I want my fucking arm sleeve, you know?

545
00:37:08,781 --> 00:37:09,022
Rym: Yeah.

546
00:37:09,203 --> 00:37:16,060
Rym: Well, I looked through my pile of art I bought for the last four years at Otakon, and there's a bunch of dozens and dozens of little prints and crafts I bought.

547
00:37:17,161 --> 00:37:23,200
Rym: And of all of them, not a single one didn't include licensed characters in some pseudo-legal way.

548
00:37:24,500 --> 00:37:24,983
Guest: Exactly.

549
00:37:25,103 --> 00:37:28,700
Guest: And what that does in spirit, you know, we'll get onto practicality in a second.

550
00:37:28,800 --> 00:37:33,400
Guest: In spirit, that takes away the entire reason for having an artist's alley, for having a gathering of people.

551
00:37:33,900 --> 00:37:37,760
Guest: I mean, the whole purpose of a convention is to gather with like-minded people.

552
00:37:38,243 --> 00:37:40,636
Guest: It's not really to go and attend panels.

553
00:37:40,736 --> 00:37:49,100
Guest: Yeah, you can do that, but isn't the real purpose of being here to do something you normally can't, to be an otaku amongst otaku, to be amongst your own people?

554
00:37:49,620 --> 00:37:53,760
Guest: And yet here we are in a state where our own people are being repressed from within.

555
00:37:54,282 --> 00:37:57,200
Guest: I hate using words like that, but it's no less true.

556
00:37:57,620 --> 00:38:05,860
Guest: The powers that be have taken it upon themselves to impose restrictions on something that they are supposed to be supporting and defending.

557
00:38:06,544 --> 00:38:11,351
Guest: I'm not saying that it is our fundamental right for an artist's alley, but as part of Otakon, it's integral.

558
00:38:11,692 --> 00:38:13,400
Guest: It's like trying to live without a liver.

559
00:38:13,781 --> 00:38:15,379
Guest: You can do it, but it ain't going to be fun.

560
00:38:17,243 --> 00:38:26,460
Rym: Well, I guess since we want to wrap this up at some point, I'd like to ask you in regarding the Save Artist Alley live journal community, what can we do?

561
00:38:26,680 --> 00:38:35,120
Rym: What can concern fans who want to express similarly their disagreement with Otakon's policy or any sort of disagreement with this in general?

562
00:38:35,180 --> 00:38:36,067
Rym: So what can they do?

563
00:38:36,228 --> 00:38:37,840
Rym: What is Save Artist Alley doing?

564
00:38:38,720 --> 00:38:41,680
Guest: Well, first of all, Save Artist Alley has a couple of things going on at this time.

565
00:38:42,140 --> 00:38:48,566
Guest: We are trying to get together a sort of modus operandi, who we are, what we really want to do, and how we are going to go about it.

566
00:38:49,129 --> 00:38:56,040
Guest: I suggested a couple of things including, first off, trying to engage Otacorp Incorporated as paying members.

567
00:38:56,640 --> 00:38:58,920
Guest: When you sign up for Otakon, you are not just signing up for an event.

568
00:38:59,420 --> 00:39:03,380
Guest: Under the regulations of the Baltimore Convention Center, we are members of Otacorp.

569
00:39:03,481 --> 00:39:04,667
Guest: We are coming for a big meeting.

570
00:39:04,687 --> 00:39:12,852
Guest: And as shareholders, if you want to use that term, we have a right to understand what is going on with our Board of Directors, and we have a right to make changes, appeals,

571
00:39:12,912 --> 00:39:13,415
Guest: etc.,

572
00:39:13,556 --> 00:39:14,200
Guest: as we see fit.

573
00:39:14,881 --> 00:39:33,600
Guest: What I want them to see with Save Artist Alley is an organized rational place where people can come together and assess their own abilities to put pressure on Otacorp, on the Board of Directors, on the Artist Alley people, in order to effect the change to restore Artist Alley to the state that it was in before this all came down.

574
00:39:34,080 --> 00:39:37,152
Guest: What we are doing is setting up a single point of contact.

575
00:39:37,373 --> 00:39:41,448
Guest: There is nothing really concrete as of yet, but we are getting petitions going.

576
00:39:41,830 --> 00:39:47,031
Guest: We are even considering contacting the public relations groups for the industry in case this does come to it.

577
00:39:47,051 --> 00:39:54,102
Guest: The last thing we want to do is call down thunder upon ourselves, but if it comes to it, we may very well need to go up to Funimation, a.d.v.

578
00:39:54,122 --> 00:40:06,451
Guest: Jimmy Onn, and say, "Hey, we would like for you to grant a license for anyone in this area of Otakon to make use of your intellectual property in the way that we see fit as artists, and we will engage the following conditions.

579
00:40:06,591 --> 00:40:08,220
Guest: We won't sell any of your stuff.

580
00:40:08,620 --> 00:40:09,865
Guest: We are just going to do our own drawings,

581
00:40:09,945 --> 00:40:10,287
Guest: etc.,

582
00:40:10,327 --> 00:40:10,728
Guest: etc.".

583
00:40:11,491 --> 00:40:22,294
Guest: If necessary, Save Artist Alley will become, and this is what I hope against, it will become a bulwark to where people can gather and actively put pressure on the powers that be.

584
00:40:22,856 --> 00:40:23,318
Guest: I like Jim Bolz.

585
00:40:23,880 --> 00:40:25,828
Guest: I like what he is doing to at least get things in line.

586
00:40:26,209 --> 00:40:34,660
Guest: I don't believe he has anything to do with this policy decision, and I believe what he can do is understand that we are your people, Jim.

587
00:40:35,040 --> 00:40:38,334
Guest: We are the ones that want to put money in this con's pockets.

588
00:40:38,736 --> 00:40:39,740
Guest: We want to keep it strong.

